event_name: a16z AI Infra x AGI House Paper Reading Event
event_description: a16z AI Infra x AGI House: Deep Research Agents with Test-Time Diffusion üìç AGI House ‚Ä¢ üóì Tech Week (Apply to attend. Space is limited.) Large language models are increasingly capable, but they‚Äôre still prone to one of their most frustrating and fundamental flaws: hallucinations. Why do models confidently state things that aren‚Äôt true, and why is this problem so stubborn? OpenAI's recent work on "Why Language Models Hallucinate" (https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.04664) argues that the root cause lies in how models are trained and evaluated. Current benchmarks reward guessing over honesty, incentivizing models to produce errors instead of admitting uncertainty. The paper reframes hallucinations not as mysterious glitches, but as predictable byproducts of next-word prediction and scoreboard design, and shows how better evaluation methods could shift model behavior. This reading group will dive into: *The core idea: how hallucinations arise from statistical training dynamics and evaluation incentives. *Why it matters: implications for model reliability, trust, and safe deployment of LLMs. *Hands-on discussion: what uncertainty-aware evaluations could look like, and how this perspective challenges common myths about hallucination. üî¨ Spotlight Paper Why Language Models Hallucinate (Ofir Nachum, Edwin Zhang, Adam Tauman Kalai, et al., 2025) We‚Äôre excited to have Ofir Nachum and Edwin Zhang joining us to kick off the discussion. This work has generated significant buzz in the research community over the past month, and we‚Äôll use the session to critically analyze its insights, from the statistical roots of hallucination to the design of future evals. Hosted by AGI House x a16z AI Infra. See you there to explore the frontier of LLM reliability! ‚ö° This event is a part of #SFTechWeek‚Äîa week of events hosted by VCs and startups to bring together the tech ecosystem. Learn more at www.tech-week.com.

event_name: APIs to AI: Infrastructure repurposed
event_description: As AI agents move to production, a critical infrastructure gap has emerged: how to securely connect AI systems to existing tools and data. Model Context Protocols (MCPs) are emerging as a standard solution, and companies building production implementations are discovering surprising insights. This fireside chat brings together Jon Dahl (Co-founder and CEO, Mux) and Michael Grinich (Founder and CEO, WorkOS)‚Äîtwo technical founders who have shipped production MCP integrations. Mux discovered that years of focus on video infrastructure had created valuable primitives that were the perfect AI building blocks such as storyboard extraction for content moderation, while WorkOS solved the enterprise authentication challenges essential for secure deployments. Both saw a broader pattern: established API businesses often have infrastructure that becomes incredibly valuable for AI workflows, even when not originally designed for that purpose. This raises questions about how companies should evaluate existing assets for AI integration. Expect a candid conversation about technical realities, integration speed, and strategic considerations. Two founders discussing what works, what doesn't, and how the MCP ecosystem is rapidly evolving. This event is a part of #SFTechWeek‚Äîa week of events hosted by VCs and startups to bring together the tech ecosystem. Learn more at www.tech-week.com.

event_name: Smart Crutch: $55B Evidence-Based Savings
event_description: At this exclusive Tech Week session, Ilya Popov, Founder of ComeBack Mobility, will present how our FDA-cleared Smart Crutch Device enables evidence-based, personalized weight-bearing rehabilitation ‚Äî accelerating bone healing and reducing costly complications. The session will feature real patient cases and preliminary results from four ongoing clinical trials, highlighting both clinical and economic impact. Current reimbursement already covers device placement and patient biofeedback training, while trials are designed to expand reimbursement to device usage. Early data indicate a breakthrough impact ‚Äî cutting the average radiographic healing time for tibia fractures in half (from 24 to 12 weeks). With proven compliance improvements (4x at NYU Langone) and a potential $55B annual payer savings, our technology is positioned to redefine the standard of care in orthopedic rehabilitation. event_name: AI in Service of LifeLanguages
event_description: This salon invites discussion on LifeLanguage companies and their use of AI as a force for good in healthcare. LifeLanguage companies specialize in building new AI models to understand the languages of life‚Äîproteins, RNA, and DNA. These companies differ from traditional biotech in that they investigate these languages not with wet-lab approaches but with GPUs. AlphaFold is a leading example in this nascent space and won the Nobel Prize last year. Since then, many startups have modeled their teams after the AlphaFold team, generating sister models that rearrange protein space to form combinations that would have taken evolution hundreds of millions of years to create. These new rearrangements have special properties for curing human disease, strengthening agriculture, and improving manufacturing. At Ecotone, our mission is to go beyond refining AlphaFold and pioneer the next frontier. Our vision is a model we call Hawaiian Diamond, capable of reading the human genome-as-a-first-language. The goal is to create a system that can generate the GPS coordinates needed by DNA-guided medications (e.g., CRISPRs) to cure all 10,000 genetic diseases. This will improve the lives of approximately 800 million people. A key design element is that the model will use one generalizable phenotype for all genetic diseases‚Äîand indeed for any observable feature. Once the coordinates for all 10,000 diseases are unearthed, the model will continue to annotate the genome, generating meaning for mysterious, unresolved sections of our DNA. This brings us closer to understanding the genome-as-a-first-language. Come and discuss over champagne and oysters (thanks to our sponsors) at a secret cozy space. Speakers include: (TBC) Format: Presentation followed by conversation and good vibes. This event is a part of #SFTechWeek‚Äîa week of events hosted by VCs and startups to bring together the tech ecosystem. Learn more at www.tech-week.com.

event_description: COME roll out with local SF trailblazers, D5 Weather Reporters, FriYEAH morning along mystical 8.5m/13.7km Bay To Breakers (B2B) route. Goal = shake out your shakies, to get blood moving +++++++++++++++ +++++++++++++++ SF GREEN BELT MOVEMENT pathway = ‚Äã1 Peace love riot up Market Street (home of endemic Western tiger swallowtail butterfly^) > 2 By United Plaza Skate Park (& Twitter) > 3 Take (hi grade) Page Slow Street > 4 Alamo Square Park (Victorian Painted Ladies) > 5 In Hendrix Haight Panhandle > 6 Thru Golden Gate Park > 7 Blow blessings to Naga (Sea Serpent) > 8 Ocean Beach, Sunset Dunes @ Pacheco https://sunsetdunes.org Rejuvenate in orchestral waves. Try surfing, boogie boarding, tai-ching, napping or flying a kite. Tap in & tune up -- #B2Bsempre +++++++++++++++ +++++++++++++++ Explore the most popular #fingbestSF city attractions intimately and energetically with soulful freestyle folks. NOTE: ^https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/a-butterfly-species-settles-in-san-franciscos-market-street-2071710 - Halloween costume is encouraged and optional. If you need a Halloween idea, check out the legendary Piedmont Boutique costume shop (in Haight Ashbury): https://www.piedmontboutique.com - Embark at your own risk. Know your own limits. - Mind you Bay to Breakers has been held for 113 years, first taking place on New Year's Day in 1912. The race was created to help lift the spirits of San Franciscans after the 1906 earthquake and fire. B2B is one of the world's oldest and longest consecutively run annual footraces. ^^ Men's B2B record = Kenya's #SammyKitwara set in 2009, posting a time of 33:31 ^^ Women's B2B record = Kenya's #LinethChepkurui set in 2010, posting a time of 38:07 ‚ÄãMeet up? Ride START = @ 9am DT SF FiDi by fountain ~Ferry Building Leave as a group promptly @ 9:30am FAQs: 1 WTF is The Alamo Park? 2 Do parrots hawks blue jays & seagulls all fight with crows? 3 Coyote or off leash emotional support dog? 4 Is that an actual heron crane or a statue? 5 How did those bison escape the mass destruction of colonialism? 6 Are humpback whale rainbows visible in the fog? 7 Why the V brown pelican formation? 8 Can I exchange my crypto into LIVE sand dollars? ++++++++++++++++ We ride rain or shine. Register for ride route map details. We can NOT wait to show you this extraordinary famous roadway. Cost? $50 per person NOTE: First 5 event attendees, win a D5WR shirt ($45 value) to support: bullet train& bus& bike& butt movement. Space is limited. Register NOW to save your spot. RSVP below to dork out w/ sustainable transportation lovers. DONATIONS of course greatly appreciated: account.venmo.com/u/fennel-wolcott-doyle ++++++++++++++++++++++ ++++++++++++++++++++++ Why District 5 Weather Reporters (D5WR)? It is our honor to present this unmatched urban Third Space, rich with wildlife, after 6+ years of D5WR advocacy efforts, in accordance with 8-80 Cities design principles: https://www.880cities.org Our San Francisco city Green Beltway goes from Tenderloin/Fillmore inner-city to the breath taking expansive Pacific ocean surf beach coastline shore of monumental ancient sand dunes. Fennel Doyle, who created D5WR -- a STEAM crusade to boost regenerative energy, modal shift & the green economy -- was nearly murdered on this very route 14 years ago. She is a NYC Parsons School of Design Dean's List graduate, NCAA Division 1 Ivy League Champion (with Brown University Women's Soccer team), road runner, scuba diver, dancer and acclaimed solar punk artist. She was hit by a car driver (AKA "Death Monster") which broke both her legs simultaneously, while she was going to Ocean Beach, to catch the Men's World Surf Competition of American OG Kelly Slater vs rising Brazilian superstar Gabriel Medina. She was released from the hospital on 11/11/11, bionic, with a titanium right leg. Luckily, Fennel fully recovered from the crash, and was able to reproduce a child. In 2020, Fennel created D5WR when schools closed during COVID for 2 years. "In the dark shadow of death*", Fennel and her (then 7 YO) son began going to the beach park together seeking life, energy, and observation-based learning flow state, as school. D5WR campaigned tirelessly to unlock the path for all, forever, to create health for future generations, and particularly for Black & broke folks living in the city. Health = Wealth. We go hard to clear our minds and ideate. We keep going. We hold space for youthful freestyle regenerative energy to compound peace. https://www.strava.com/athletes/67012557 #carfreeisSEXY "Aren't You Tireddddddddd?" - Kendrick Lamar "Make up is science" - Kryolan "Let's work" - Prince *Wu-Tang Clan We acknowledge the importance of Native American Ohlone stewardship of this land horticulture for 10,000+ years. As well as the need for grassroots action, community empowerment, and the deep connection between environmental health and social well-being, as exemplified by the powerful legacy of the Green Belt Movement's founder, Wangarƒ© Maathai, in Kenya. D5WR is proud to share our core beloved city green pathway with you and yours. We recently transformed some of the deadliest city streets into the most vibrant accessible efficient streets ‚Äî safe for all living beings (including DT SF office commuters). #B2Bsempre Ride Event deeply inspired by: M-PESA, Straus Family Creamery, American-Kenyan farmer Kelis, Farming for Hope, Walk SF, SF Bay Area Families For Safe Streets, Rich City Rides, Church of Eight Wheels, Streets For All, Bay Area Outreach and Recreation Program (BORP), Nature in the City, SF New Farm, Westside Collective, and SambaFunk Arts. event_name: Brisket, Bots, & Breakthroughs
event_description: Discover how Mindbeam‚Äôs Litespark is setting a new industry bar‚Äîdelivering up to 6x faster LLM pre-training, doubling token and batch throughput, and reducing energy costs by over 50% for both startups and enterprises. In this dynamic panel, Mindbeam founder Nii Osae, Principal Research Scientist Moinul Rahat, PhD, and Datology founder Ari Morcos will discuss how advances in training models and agentic AI make real-world deployment possible at scale. Join us by the fire(side) chat with BBQ to connect directly with the founders of Mindbeam and Datology, share bold ideas, and accelerate your LLM journey. What We Will Cover: - Analyze Mindbeam‚Äôs Litespark improvements to training efficiency, including measured speed-ups in LLM pre-training, throughput, and resource utilization across practical ML workflows. - Examine Datology‚Äôs approach to agentic automation, synthetic data, and architectural implications for scalable, robust multi-modal models and real-world enterprise applications. - Review concrete deployment patterns for generative models, detailing the trade-offs, reproducible benchmarks, and lessons from actual implementations by technical teams. - Discuss case studies with a focus on design decisions, failure modes, and optimizations as experienced by organizations deploying Mindbeam and Datology in production settings. - Engage in a participatory Q&A: attendees are encouraged to raise deep technical issues, probe modeling choices, and share practical challenges with panelists who welcome nuanced discussion‚Äînot surface-level hype. Speakers: - Nii Osae | 2nd time founder with 10+ years of experience in machine learning, applied neural cognitive architecture, scaling large AI applications. He published scientific research papers on efficient training of large language models and code-generating LLMs in collaboration with Nvidia, AWS, Huggingface, and ServiceNow. He is also a Forbes 30 Under 30 recipient. - Moinul Rahat, PhD | Moinul is an expert in Quantum Machine Learning (QML) and Quantum Optimization techniques to address complex challenges in particle physics and beyond. He has a PhD from the University of Florida, and was a Postdoctoral Fellow at University of Southampton and University of Valencia. He developed a hybrid Quantum Generative Adversarial Network (QGAN) architecture with a quantum generator and classical discriminator utilizing PennyLane and PyTorch. - Ari Morcos | Ari is the CEO and co-founder of DatologyAI, where the team is dedicated to helping customers build better AI models through improved data quality and methodology. Join us by the fire(side) chat with BBQ to connect directly with the founders of Mindbeam and Datology, share bold ideas, and accelerate your LLM journey. event_name: How to be visible to AI Search
event_description: AI-powered platforms are reshaping how tech companies gain visibility, with ChatGPT leading referral traffic across industries and Perplexity and Gemini gaining ground in specific verticals. This workshop will focus on the important conversation underway between technologists, investors, and human rights-concerned citizens, with a focus on identifying where strong accountability drives value creation and mitigates risk. With AI reshaping industries at unprecedented speed, we are in a pivotal moment to understand and build strategies that look at the human rights implications of tech investments. Now is the time for intentional conversations across the spectrum, from tech investors to digital rights organizations, so we can develop strategies to embed human rights considerations into tech investment approaches while supporting the companies and investors leading in their consideration of their societal impact. This workshop presents a compelling, data-driven discussion around the business case for human rights-respecting investments, offering investors actionable insights to drive outperformance and reduce exposure to unrewarded risk. Robots, drones, aircrafts, and autonomous vehicles will generate vast streams of synthetic data, pushing a profound upgrade of the digital realm and crafting a digital reality that surpasses the natural world. Now is the critical window to shape this future. We stand at a paradigm crossroads: from ‚Äúhuman value comes from our labor‚Äù to ‚Äúhuman value comes from who we are.‚Äù I believe in this shift, and I have named it EuReality. Inspired by eusociality‚Äîthe highest form of social organization in biology, where individuals thrive through cooperation, specialization, and shared purpose‚Äîeureality reimagines this principle for technology. It embodies distributed intelligence: machines and systems acting collectively, like a superorganism. In the digital realm, eureality is not just an upgrade; it is an ecosystem of intelligent machines, smart hardware, and synthetic data working together to create a reality more connected, adaptive, and transformative than ever before. üëÄ This event is a part of #SFTechWeek‚Äîa week of events hosted by VCs and startups to bring together the tech ecosystem. Facilitated Discussion (15 min): Group representatives share highlights of discussions. Facilitator highlights overlapping patterns and differences. 5. Increase Resilience and Wisdom Practice (10 min): Facilitator guides individuals on how they can redirect from saboteur to sage in the moment. 6. event_name: Verifiers - Fireside Chat with Will Brown
event_description: No slides, no pitches, just war stories, patterns and anti patterns from the engineers who built RL verifiers. In RLVR, the policy learns whatever the verifier rewards. If the verifier is leaky, exploitable, or miscalibrated, you‚Äôre training on lies. This fireside is a candid, practitioner-level dive with builder who have shipped multiple verifiers across tasks (safety, code, tool use). We‚Äôll hit: - What a good verifier actually is: pairwise vs scalar scoring, sparse rewards, decomposition etc. - Generalization under shift: preventing policy-chasing, leakage, and ‚Äúreward hacking by spec ambiguity.‚Äù - Calibration & coverage: thresholds, selective prediction, human-in-the-loop only where it moves expected utility. - Sparse reward tasks: how to design verifiers when feedback is naturally scarce - detecting rare successes, using proxy signals without collapsing to spec drift, and tricks like trajectory-level verification or hierarchical reward shaping. - If time permits: RL environments and how verifiers are the key. Non-consensus takes we‚Äôll debate: - Verifiers should abstain a lot more (prevent the model from training on the wrong signal) - Train/Configure verifiers on artifacts (traces/tests), not just text. - Optimize for uncertainty quality, not mean score. Who should come: folks shipping LLMs, agents, RLVR stacks; anyone who‚Äôs been burned by a ‚Äúgood‚Äù reward model. Leave with a concrete checklist, sample specs, and a playbook to make your verifier the bottleneck on truth. This event is a part of #SFTechWeek‚Äîa week of events hosted by VCs and startups to bring together the tech ecosystem. Learn more at www.tech-week.com.

event_name: a16z AI Infra x AGI House Paper Reading Event
event_description: a16z AI Infra x AGI House: Deep Research Agents with Test-Time Diffusion üìç AGI House ‚Ä¢ üóì Tech Week (Apply to attend. Space is limited.) Large language models are increasingly capable, but they‚Äôre still prone to one of their most frustrating and fundamental flaws: hallucinations. Why do models confidently state things that aren‚Äôt true, and why is this problem so stubborn? OpenAI's recent work on "Why Language Models Hallucinate" (https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.04664) argues that the root cause lies in how models are trained and evaluated. Current benchmarks reward guessing over honesty, incentivizing models to produce errors instead of admitting uncertainty. The paper reframes hallucinations not as mysterious glitches, but as predictable byproducts of next-word prediction and scoreboard design, and shows how better evaluation methods could shift model behavior. This reading group will dive into: *The core idea: how hallucinations arise from statistical training dynamics and evaluation incentives. *Why it matters: implications for model reliability, trust, and safe deployment of LLMs. *Hands-on discussion: what uncertainty-aware evaluations could look like, and how this perspective challenges common myths about hallucination. üî¨ Spotlight Paper Why Language Models Hallucinate (Ofir Nachum, Edwin Zhang, Adam Tauman Kalai, et al., 2025) We‚Äôre excited to have Ofir Nachum and Edwin Zhang joining us to kick off the discussion. This work has generated significant buzz in the research community over the past month, and we‚Äôll use the session to critically analyze its insights, from the statistical roots of hallucination to the design of future evals. Hosted by AGI House x a16z AI Infra. See you there to explore the frontier of LLM reliability! ‚ö° This event is a part of #SFTechWeek‚Äîa week of events hosted by VCs and startups to bring together the tech ecosystem.
